    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nCurrently in https://cython.readthedocs.io/en/latest/src/userguide/source_files_and_compilation.html#globally there are several mentions of `# distutils: ...` special header comment, and exactly one mention of `# cython: ...` special header comment.\r\n\r\nThey seems interchangeable, and nowhere is the difference explained.\r\n\r\nMaybe it's a good idea to clarify the documentation what's the difference. (Or maybe one is preferable to the other.)\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n_No response_\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\n_No response_\n\n### OS\n\n_No response_\n\n### Python version\n\n_No response_\n\n### Cython version\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "They aren't interchangeable. The `# distutils:` ones affect things that are specifically passed to `Extension` in setup.py (e.g. C include paths, C vs C++), and the `# cython:` ones control how Cython interprets things.\r\n\r\nI agree this could probably be clarified though. The \"source files and compilation\" page is due a bit of a revamp I think, just because it's got huge and unwieldy.",
